frameDefinitions: An Agent finishes an Activity, which can no longer logically continue.
An Agent or Cause causes a Process or State to end.
An Author creates a Text, either written, such as a letter, or spoken, such as a speech,  that contains meaningful linguistic tokens, and may have a particular Addressee in mind.
An Agent or Cause causes an Entity to change, either in its category membership or in terms of the value of an Attribute.
Two (or more) people (the Parties, also encodable as Party_1 and Party_2) have an agreement.
frameExamples: Jason <t>completed</t> grading the papers late Sunday night.
Bush may <t>lift</t> sanctions on his own, despite opposition.
I <t>penned</t> a letter concerning racism to Congress.
Our storylines follows the saga outlined by the Ultima Series, but we have <t>modified</t> it in order to make our writing more cohesive.
The US and Russia have an <t>agreement</t> to share early warning data on missile launches.
listRoleDefinitions: This role identifies the <fen>Agent</fen> who has finished an <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Activity</fen> that the <fen>Agent</fen> has finished.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Activity</fen> finishes.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Agent</fen> finishes the <fen>Activity</fen>.
A <fen>Process</fen> which is ended by the <fen>Agent</fen> or <fen>Cause</fen>.
The individual who causes the <fen>Process</fen> or <fen>State</fen> to end.
An event that causes the <fen>Process</fen> or <fen>State</fen> to end.
A <fen>State</fen> which is ended by the <fen>Agent</fen> or <fen>Cause</fen>.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Process</fen> or <fen>State</fen> is ended.
The location where the <fen>Process</fen> or <fen>State</fen> is caused to end.
The <fen>Author</fen> produces a particular <fen>Text</fen>.
The entity which results from the act of writing or speaking.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> at which the text is created.
Where the event takes place.
The sentient entity that effects a change in the <fen>Entity</fen>.
The category of which the <fen>Entity</fen> is a member before the <fen>Agent</fen> causes a change.
The category that the <fen>Entity</fen> belongs to after it has undergone the change.
The value that the <fen>Attribute</fen> assumes as a result of the change that the <fen>Entity</fen> is caused to undergo.
The value that the <fen>Attribute</fen> has before the change takes place.
The abstract or concrete thing or situation that the <fen>Agent</fen> causes to change.
The time at which the change of the <fen>Entity</fen> is caused.
The location where the change of the <fen>Entity</fen> is caused.

The individual or individuals that form the more prominent (i.e. agentive) party of the agreement, as compared with <fen>Party_2</fen>. That is, <fen>Party_1</fen> is generally encoded as the External Argument of verbs, and peripheral FEs that do not make reference to the event itself generally make reference to <fen>Party_1</fen>. Thus <fen>Manner</fen> is construed to be that of <fen>Party_1</fen>, not necessarily that of <fen>Party_2</fen> or the group of <fen>Parties</fen> as a whole.
The semantically (and grammatically) less prominent participant (or group of participants) in the agreement. It is generally encoded within a prepositional phrase (e.g. headed by with).
An expression of the commitment of the <fen>Parties</fen> .
<fen>Topic</fen> is a description of the domain covered by the agreement.
The group of individuals portrayed as equally involved in having an agreement.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the agreement was made.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where an agreement was made.
